name.text: 7.2.3 (Write maximum and minimum from feasibility region)

questiontext.text:
Given the following graph, and where the feasibility region is the shaded area. Find the maximum and minimum of the optimisation equation \(z = 3x-y\), subject to the constraints shown on the graph.

minimum=[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]

maximum=[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]

generalfeedback.text: Remember that the maximum and minimum of the problem occur at the corners of the feasibility region. So, in this case the coordinates of the corners are: \[ (0,4) \qquad (3/2,11/2) \qquad (6,1). \] Substituting these into the optimisation equation we have \[ \begin{align*} &(0,4): \:\:\: z = -4 \\ &(3/2,11/2): \:\:\: z = -1 \\ &(6,1): \:\:\: z = 17 \\ \end{align*} \] Hence the maximum is achieved at \((6,1)\) and is \(17\) and the minimum is achieved at \(0,4\) which is \(-4\).
